<abstract>
<title>SUMMARY</title>
<p id="P2">Haploinsufficiency of <italic>Retinoic Acid Induced 1</italic> (<italic>RAI1</italic>) causes Smith-Magenis syndrome (SMS), which is associated with diverse neurodevelopmental and behavioral symptoms as well as obesity. <italic>RAI1</italic> encodes a nuclear protein but little is known about its molecular function or the cell types responsible for SMS symptoms. Using genetically engineered mice, we found that Rai1 preferentially occupies DNA regions near active promoters and promotes the expression of a group of genes involved in circuit assembly and neuronal communication. Behavioral analyses demonstrated that pan-neural loss of Rai1 causes deficits in motor function, learning, and food intake. These SMS-like phenotypes are produced by loss of Rai1 function in distinct neuronal types: <italic>Rai1</italic> loss in inhibitory neurons or subcortical glutamatergic neurons causes learning deficits, while <italic>Rai1</italic> loss in Sim1<sup>+</sup> or SF1<sup>+</sup> cells causes obesity. By integrating molecular and organismal analyses, our study suggests potential therapeutic avenues for a complex neurodevelopmental disorder.</p>
</abstract>
